			<Body>
				<Text Type="text">
					&lt;p&gt;Abt is abbot in Dutch. You can hear a couple people pronounce it on &lt;a href="http://forvo.com/word/abt/" rel="nofollow"&gt;Forvo&lt;/a&gt;, but in the States I'd just say abbot. The top two examples are German. If you scroll down there is one Dutch speaker. For anyone unfamiliar with St. Bernardus or how a monk relates to a beer, it's an &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beer_in_Belgium#Abbey_beers" rel="nofollow"&gt;abbey beer&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;Additionally, the 12 in the name seems to refer to the beers gravity. In the &lt;a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=6eRbBAAAQBAJ&amp;amp;pg=PA302&amp;amp;lpg=PA302&amp;amp;dq=the%20beer%20bible%20the%20essential%20beer%20lovers%20guide%20st%20bernardus&amp;amp;source=bl&amp;amp;ots=FckY1o01Lh&amp;amp;sig=pFad3idMreC46j76f1OTZp6dXMY&amp;amp;hl=en&amp;amp;sa=X&amp;amp;ved=0ahUKEwio2K-I89vPAhVD5mMKHagbCMYQ6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&amp;amp;q&amp;amp;f=false" rel="nofollow"&gt;Belgian degree system&lt;/a&gt;, specific gravity is converted to degrees by subtracting 1 from the number and multiplying by 100 (there's a little history on St. Bernardus if you scroll down to pg. 305). So if the final gravity is &lt;a href="http://www.candisyrup.com/uploads/6/0/3/5/6035776/st._bernardus_abt_12_clone_-_041.pdf" rel="nofollow"&gt;1.012&lt;/a&gt; (PDF for clone recipe), crunch the numbers and you end up with 12 degrees.&lt;/p&gt;

				</Text>
			</Body>
		</Instance>
		<Instance Id="7" InstanceType="answer">
			<PostId>6397</PostId>
